Added test cases which test the public methods of the KNXCoreTypeMapper class according KNX "System Specifications, Interworking, Datapoint Types" Version 1.07.00. Some tests revealed bugs in openhab and calimero. Theses tests testing the wrong behaivour such that they don't fail.

KNXCoreTypeMapper maps Openhab's PercentType to KNX's DPT_PERCENT_U8 and vice versa. PercentType holds values from 0% to 100%, but DPT_PERCENT_U8 can hold values from 0% to 255%, where byte 0xff is 255%. A better match is DPT_SCALING (5.001) which translates byte 0xff to 100%. So, 5.001 and 5.004 should now behave as spec'd in KNX Spec.

Update serialisation code. This modification moves the 'restore from file' code from the node advancer, into the controller. Instead of creating a new node, then restoring and then having to read all the information out of the file and put it into the node, and restore all the command classes and their data, this instead reads the node file directly and uses the class created by the XML deserialiser which contains all the data that was originally serialised. This avoids having to add getter/setter methods for every new class, or bit of information that gets added to classes, or nodes in future. Once the data is deserialised from disk, some information needs to be added to the command classes and nodes - i.e. links to the controller, and to the node for a command class. ** Needs further testing **

Initial separation of node state and initialisation state Previously, the single 'stage' state flag caused problems identifying the progression of initialisation, and the actual device state. For example, if a node goes DEAD during initialisation, then we loose the information on its configuration state, so when the node is ALIVE again, we don't know what to do (i.e. where to restart initialisation). A good initialisation is imperative - we need to know all the device information so we can properly support it, so we need to restart initialisation. With this change, we have a device state (ALIVE, DEAD, FAILED) and an initialisation stage. Initialisation will progress independently of the device state. Heal will only occur if initialisation is complete.

Separate processing of received messages from COM port thread This fixes a major bug in the binding. Previously the ACK was not sent to a message from the stick until after the previous message was processed. This meant that if a message took more than 2 seconds to process, the stick would retry, and we end up with multiple messages that can not be correlated correctly with the request.

Add 'ackPending' check into serialMessage. I found that sometimes it's possible for the response to a transaction to come in before the ack from the controller. This causes the binding to send the next request but because the controller hasn't acked its request, we get a NAK. We need to therefore wait for both the response to the SendData request, and the Application Message.

Prioritise messages to battery nodes as IMMEDIATE This tries to ensure that messages to battery nodes don't get stuck at the end of the queue. When a node wakes up, we put its messages at the top of the queue to get them sent while it's still awake. This will only have an impact when the queue is not empty, but if the queue has other frames, then without this it's possible that it could take some time to actually send the message, by which time the node might be asleep again.

Update message queue priority concept 	 * Immediate: Messages that must be sent at highest priority. 	 *            Generally this is reserved for battery devices so we send 	 *            messages while they are awake. The high priority allows their 	 *            messages to jump the queue. 	 * High:      Other high priority messages 	 * Set:       Messages relating to SET commands. 	 *            This should only be used for SET type commands that need to 	 *            be responsive - eg light switches, or things that are expected 	 *            to occur quickly. 	 * Get:       Messages relating to GET commands. 	 *            Most messages relating to reading data use this priority. 	 * Config:    Messages relating to system configuration. 	 *            This can be GET or SET type commands, but these are things that 	 *            don't need to be responsive. 	 * Poll:      Messages relating to polling. 	 *            Normally these are GET commands, but the system overrides the 	 *            priority to the lowest so they don't cause any impact on the 	 *            system.
